CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS players
(
playerId INT,
playerName STRING,
playerRuns LONG
);

CREATE TABLE all_transactions AS
SELECT * FROM march_transactions
UNION SELECT * FROM april_transactions;

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION format_name(fname STRING, lname STRING)
RETURNS STRING
RETURN INITCAP(fname) || ‘ ‘ || INITCAP(lname);

Question:
Given the following command:
CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS hr_db;
In which of the following locations will the hr_db database be located?

Given the following commands:
CREATE DATABASE db_hr;
USE db_hr;
CREATE TABLE employees;
In which of the following locations will the employees table be located?

A junior data engineer accidentally executed a DELETE FROM employees command without a WHERE clause, effectively removing all records from the production table. The team needs to restore the table immediately to its state prior to this catastrophic operation.
The lead engineer runs DESCRIBE HISTORY employees to identify the correct version to restore. The output is shown below:
Graphic: DESCRIBE HISTORY output
version | timestamp | userId | userName | operation | operationParameters
4 | 07/01/2026 10:20 | 8892 | job_bot | OPTIMIZE | {"predicate": []}
3 | 07/01/2026 10:15 | 5501 | junior_dev | DELETE | {"predicate": "true"}
2 | 07/01/2026 10:10 | 4402 | etl_user | UPDATE | {"predicate": "id > 100"}
1 | 07/01/2026 9:00 | 4402 | etl_user | MERGE | {"predicate": "..."}
0 | 07/01/2026 8:00 | 9901 | admin | TABLE | {"description": "..."}
Based on this history, the goal is to revert the table to the state exactly after the UPDATE operation (Version 2) but before the DELETE operation (Version 3). Which two SQL commands successfully achieve this restoration? (Select two)
